# FMAttack: Exploiting Authentication Gaps in the CXL Fabric Manager API for Multi-Tenant Memory Hijacking

**M.N. Srivatsa Bharadwaj**
Samsung Semiconductor Research India (SSRI), Bengaluru, Karnataka, India
srivatsa.mn@samsung.com

---

## Abstract

Compute Express Link (CXL) 2.0–4.0 defines a Fabric Manager (FM) API for orchestrating multi-tenant memory pools, dynamic capacity regions, and port-based routing across disaggregated CXL fabrics. We identify five normative gaps (GAP-1 through GAP-5) in the CXL specification: the FM API command payload tables contain no authentication fields, SPDM session binding for FM commands is explicitly optional, and the software routing table maintained by the FM can diverge silently from the hardware routing table in the CXL switch—leaving the FM ownership table as the sole, unverified enforcement boundary. Exploiting these gaps, we construct four concrete attacks: VPPB-REBIND (ATK-1), which hijacks a virtual PCI-to-PCI bridge across tenants in 1.85 µs; PORTDOS (ATK-2), which disables shared physical ports in 2.14 µs; DCDRAIN (ATK-3), which silently revokes dynamic memory capacity from a live LLM workload in 1.98 µs; and TUNNELSPOOF (ATK-4), which injects fabricated commands through a CXL Tunnel in 1.42 µs. All four attacks are validated via a Python-based CXL fabric simulator over 1,000 Monte-Carlo iterations, each achieving a 100% success rate. We propose four complementary defences—hardware-anchored ownership registers, SPDM + RATS attestation binding, orchestrator-signed command tokens, and per-tenant hardware isolation—and provide a concrete standardisation roadmap for the CXL Consortium to elevate FM authentication from a SHOULD to a SHALL requirement.

**Index Terms**—CXL, Fabric Manager, FMAPI, MCTP, memory security, side-channel, SPDM, multi-tenant, disaggregated memory, dynamic capacity device

---

## I. INTRODUCTION

Compute Express Link (CXL) has emerged as the dominant interconnect standard for memory disaggregation in hyperscale and AI data-centres. CXL 2.0 introduced pooled memory and fabric switching; CXL 3.0 extended this to multi-level fabrics and peer-to-peer coherence; CXL 4.0 further refined Dynamic Capacity Devices (DCD), Port-Based Routing (PBR), and the Fabric Manager (FM) API that orchestrates all of these components.

The FM API is the control plane for every multi-tenant CXL fabric. It is the sole mechanism through which memory regions are allocated across tenants, physical ports are enabled or disabled, and virtual PCI-to-PCI bridges (vPPBs) are bound to logical devices. Despite its privileged position, the FM API has received almost no security scrutiny: prior CXL security research has focused on side-channel leakage in coherency traffic, memory encryption, and SPDM key exchange at device bring-up. The FM control plane—the entity that decides which tenant owns which memory—has been assumed trusted.

**This assumption is wrong.**

We make the following contributions:

1. We perform the first systematic security audit of the CXL FM API command set—spanning physical port management (0x5100–0x510F), vPPB management (0x5200–0x520F), MLD management (0x5400–0x540F), DCD management (0x5600–0x5605), and switch/tunnel management (0x5700–0x5716)—and identify five normative specification gaps (GAP-1 through GAP-5) that, collectively, leave FM command authentication undefined by the CXL standard.
2. We demonstrate that the MCTP transport used by FM API allows any MCTP-capable process on the network to issue FM commands directly to a CXL switch, bypassing the FM software daemon entirely.
3. We construct and simulate four end-to-end attacks (ATK-1 through ATK-4) that exploit these gaps to achieve cross-tenant memory hijacking, denial-of-service, capacity starvation, and command injection, all within 2.15 µs latency.
4. We propose a four-layer defence architecture and a concrete standardisation roadmap for CXL 5.0.

The remainder of the paper is organised as follows. Section II provides CXL and FM API background. Section III analyses the five normative gaps. Section IV defines the threat model. Section V presents the four attacks, with message-sequence diagrams for each. Section VI describes evaluation methodology and results. Section VII proposes defences and the standardisation roadmap. Section VIII surveys related work. Section IX concludes.

