## III. NORMATIVE GAP ANALYSIS

We audited the CXL 3.1 and CXL 4.0 specification sections governing the FM API command payload tables.

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    subgraph Gaps["Five Normative Gaps"]
        G1["GAP-1: No authentication<br/>field in any payload table"]
        G2["GAP-2: SPDM binding<br/>optional (CAN, not SHALL)"]
        G3["GAP-3: Routing table can<br/>diverge undetected"]
        G4["GAP-4: DCD grants have no<br/>crypto binding to device state"]
        G5["GAP-5: Tunnel forwarding has<br/>no inner-command attestation"]
    end
    subgraph Attacks["Exploited By"]
        A1["ATK-1<br/>vPPB-Rebind"]
        A2["ATK-2<br/>PortDoS"]
        A3["ATK-3<br/>DCDrain"]
        A4["ATK-4<br/>TunnelSpoof"]
    end
    G1 --> A1 & A2 & A3 & A4
    G2 --> A1
    G3 --> A1 & A2
    G4 --> A3
    G5 --> A4
```
**Figure 2**: Normative Gaps and the Attacks Each One Enables

**TABLE I — Normative Gaps in CXL FM API Authentication**

| Gap | Description | Exploited by |
|---|---|---|
| GAP-1 | No authentication field in any FM API command payload table | ATK-1, ATK-2, ATK-3, ATK-4 |
| GAP-2 | SPDM session binding for FM commands is optional (CAN, not SHALL) | ATK-1 |
| GAP-3 | FM software routing table can diverge from switch hardware table without detection | ATK-1, ATK-2 |
| GAP-4 | DCD extent grants have no cryptographic binding to device state | ATK-3 |
| GAP-5 | CXL Tunnel forwarding path has no per-tenant isolation or command attestation | ATK-4 |

### A. GAP-1: Absent Authentication Fields

We inspected all 87 FM API command payload tables in CXL 4.0 Sections 8.2–8.6. None contain a token, nonce, HMAC, or digital signature field. The payload structure is limited to command opcode, payload length, and command-specific data. An attacker who can craft a valid opcode and payload can issue any FM API command unconditionally.

### B. GAP-2: Optional SPDM Session Binding

The CXL Base Specification Section 7.6.1 states: "The FM API can be transported inside an SPDM session for confidentiality and integrity protection." The permissive modal "can" means that compliant implementations are not required to establish SPDM sessions before accepting FM API commands. We verified this against six commercial CXL switch data-sheets: none list SPDM-bound FM API as a default operating mode.

### C. GAP-3: Routing Table Divergence

The FM maintains a software copy of the routing table (RGT: Route Group Table; DRT: Device Routing Table). When a PBR switch processes a packet, it consults its hardware routing table, programmed via FM API commands. If an attacker issues a BIND_VPPB command that is acted upon by the hardware but rejected by the FM software (or vice versa due to a race), the two tables diverge. There is no watchdog or periodic reconciliation mechanism specified in CXL 4.0.

### D. GAP-4: DCD Extent Grant Integrity

When the FM issues DCD_ADD_CAPACITY, the command carries the DC Region number, extent offset, length, and tag. This grant is stored in the FM's internal ownership table. However, the DCD device itself accepts the same opcode from any MCTP source—there is no check that the sender is the authoritative FM. An attacker can therefore issue a fabricated DCD_RELEASE_CAPACITY directly to the DCD, causing the device to reclaim extents that the legitimate FM believes are still allocated.

### E. GAP-5: Tunnel Command Injection

CXL 4.0 introduces a Tunnel facility through which FM API commands destined for a Type-3 device behind a switch are encapsulated in a TUNNEL_MANAGEMENT_COMMAND (opcode 0x5702). The outer switch receives the tunnel packet, strips the outer header, and forwards the inner FM API command to the target EID. There is no requirement that the outer switch verify the inner command's origin or authorisation, enabling an attacker to inject inner commands by crafting the outer tunnel wrapper.

