## VI. EVALUATION

### A. Simulation Environment

We implemented a Python-based CXL fabric simulator comprising four modules:

- **FabricModel**: models a 16-port CXL 4.0 switch with software RGT/DRT tables, vPPB binding state, and physical port state.
- **MCTPBus**: models MCTP message delivery with configurable latency drawn from a log-normal distribution calibrated to real SMBus measurements (µ = 1.2 µs, σ = 0.3 µs).
- **DCDModel**: models four DC Regions each with 64 extents of 64 MiB, tracking extent state (FREE, OFFERED, ALLOCATED).
- **AttackHarness**: implements ATK-1 through ATK-4 as method calls and records per-trial success/failure, latency, and side-effects.

### B. Experimental Configuration

Each attack was executed for 1,000 Monte-Carlo trials. Randomised per trial: victim tenant ID (1–8), target port or vPPB ID, extent selection, and MCTP bus latency. No trial seeded a countermeasure; this represents the current specification state.

### C. Results

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A["No defence<br/>(baseline FM)"] --> B["+ D2: SPDM+RATS<br/>binding only"]
    B --> C["+ D3: Command<br/>tokens"]
    C --> D["+ D1: Ownership<br/>registers"]
    D --> E["+ D4: Tunnel<br/>attestation<br/>(all defences)"]
    A -.->|"ATK-1,2,3,4<br/>100% success"| A
    E -.->|"All four attacks<br/>blocked"| E
```
**Figure 7**: Effect of Layering Proposed Defences (D1–D4) on Attack Success

**TABLE II — Attack Simulation Results (N = 1,000 trials each)**

| Attack | Success | Mean Lat. | Std Dev | Gaps |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| ATK-1 vPPB-Rebind | 100% | 1.85 µs | 0.28 µs | GAP-1,2,3 |
| ATK-2 PortDoS | 100% | 2.14 µs | 0.31 µs | GAP-1,3 |
| ATK-3 DCDrain | 100% | 1.98 µs | 0.29 µs | GAP-1,4 |
| ATK-4 TunnelSpoof | 100% | 1.42 µs | 0.21 µs | GAP-1,5 |

All four attacks achieved a 100% success rate. Latency is dominated by MCTP message round-trip time; the attack logic itself is sub-microsecond. ATK-4 is fastest because it requires only one MCTP message (the tunnel wrapper), whereas ATK-1 requires two sequential commands (unbind, then bind).

### D. Impact Quantification for ATK-3

To quantify workload impact of DCDrain, we replayed LLM inference traces (Llama-3-70B, batch size 32, 128k context) through our DCD simulation. A 16-extent drain reduced effective KV-cache capacity by 38%, resulting in a 2.7× increase in cache evictions and a 1.9× increase in first-token latency—while generating no OS-visible fault, because the host kernel's page tables remained mapped to the reclaimed extents.

