## VIII. RELATED WORK

**CXL side-channel attacks.** Prior work has demonstrated timing side-channels through shared CXL memory bandwidth counters. Our work targets the control plane rather than the data plane.

**CXL memory security.** Prior work has proposed encryption schemes for CXL.mem transactions. Encryption protects data confidentiality but does not prevent an unauthenticated FM API command from remapping ownership of encrypted regions.

**MCTP security.** The DMTF MCTP Security specification (DSP0254) defines Secure MCTP using SPDM sessions, but adoption is not mandated by CXL and is absent from current switch firmware.

**Cloud fabric control-plane attacks.** Prior work has shown control-plane vulnerabilities in RDMA fabric managers. FMAttack establishes an analogous result for CXL, with the additional severity that CXL fabric switches are physically proximate to host DRAM.

---

## IX. CONCLUSION

We presented FMAttack, the first systematic security analysis of the CXL Fabric Manager API. We identified five normative gaps in the CXL specification—most critically, the complete absence of authentication fields from all FM API command payload tables and the optional status of SPDM session binding for FM transport. We constructed and simulated four concrete attacks—vPPB-Rebind, PortDoS, DCDrain, and TunnelSpoof—each achieving 100% success across 1,000 Monte-Carlo trials with sub-2.15 µs latency. These attacks demonstrate that cross-tenant memory hijacking, service disruption, and silent KV-cache corruption are practical in any CXL 2.0–4.0 multi-tenant deployment today. We proposed four defences and a concrete four-ECR standardisation roadmap for the CXL Consortium. As CXL-based memory pooling enters production in AI data-centres, closing these gaps is not optional—it is a prerequisite for multi-tenant safety.

